</script>

<div class="lesson-content">

	<MaterialsList materials={[{"name":"Paper or notebook","isOptional":false},{"name":"Pens/pencils","isOptional":false},{"name":"Images or videos related to gender equality","isOptional":false},{"name":"Whiteboard or large chart paper","isOptional":false},{"name":"Markers","isOptional":false}]} {sdgColor} />

	<CustomSection title={"Scripts for Equality: Crafting Dialogue for a Gender-Equal World"} content={"<strong>(30-60 MINUTES)</strong>"} {sdgColor} />

	<Introduction content={"<p>Begin by asking students, “How can words create change?”<br>Re-introduce Global Goal 5 if needed - “Achieve gender equality and empower all women and girls”<br>Connect to scriptwriting by explaining how dialogue in stories and plays can reveal characters’ perspectives, challenge societal norms, and spark conversations about important issues like gender equality.<br>Examples:\n<ul>\n<li>Hidden Figures, <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9j6p7ajuh-E\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Bathroom Scene</a></li>\n<li>This scene highlights both racial and gender discrimination, showcasing the challenges faced by women of color in STEM fields.</li>\n<li>Mulan, <a href=\"https://www.google.com/search?sca_esv=d30728c3aa4495a6&amp;sxsrf=ADLYWIKxA7lsPI8fBjcBMYkFOhxIivtHDQ:1723769966457&amp;q=mulan+cuts+her+hair+scene&amp;tbm=vid&amp;source=lnms&amp;fbs=AEQNm0BttMAYK3zfKuhWMlJUaX3cvDtlSecvyvHP-m03X7HLDorxHq__k1r6jSUbIKwSw-obr4Wa5YBzh2lVfbpsYgu4BGFIjb-mctqPmey6MNANB2IFURIxZRbnNAVFWq69VnKATxyLewXBvAd6-DDkUERusLqS9hrO7AztHrHdGKKjA-NuJKMyMDAEFjot_ykmepyNoGPuHiLg0niWGh5Na0UUcQKc3g&amp;sa=X&amp;ved=2ahUKEwiGt5nEp_iHAxVOJUQIHexpC1gQ0pQJegQIERAB&amp;biw=1200&amp;bih=728&amp;dpr=2#fpstate=ive&amp;vld=cid:11180ccf,vid:U0FRd8BbRW4,st:0\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Hair Cut Scene</a></li>\n<li>This scene is a powerful example of a woman challenging societal expectations and proving her strength and capabilities.</li>\n<li>Legally Blonde, <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_aDYAwlYXTc\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Admissions Scene</a></li>\n<li>This scene challenges stereotypes about women who are interested in fashion and beauty, showing that intelligence and ambition are not limited by gender or outward appearance.</li>\n<li>Moana, <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sQfk2V7WUjc\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Fighting with Father Scene</a></li>\n<li>This scene empowers young girls to follow their dreams and break free from limiting expectations.</li>\n</ul></p>"} />

	<CustomSection title={"Character Development: Giving Voice to the Targets"} content={"<p>Divide students into groups, each assigned a different Global Goal 5 Target.<br>Have each group brainstorm and create two contrasting characters whose lives are directly impacted by the target. Examples:\n<ul>\n<li><em>Target 5.1 - Discrimination Against Women:</em></li>\n<li><em>Character 1:</em>  A girl who is discouraged from playing sports because \"it's not for girls.\"</li>\n<li>Character 2: Her coach who believes in her abilities and pushes her to challenge gender norms.</li>\n<li><em>Target 5.2 - Violence Against Women:</em></li>\n<li>Character 1: A woman experiencing domestic abuse, trapped in a cycle of fear and control.</li>\n<li>Character 2: A neighbor who notices the signs of abuse and offers support and resources.</li>\n<li><em>Target 5.3 - Eliminate Harmful Practices:</em></li>\n<li>Character 1: A young girl in a community where child marriage is prevalent, facing pressure to marry early.</li>\n<li>Character 2: A teacher who educates girls about their rights and empowers them to resist harmful practices.</li>\n<li><em>Target 5.4 - Recognize Unpaid Care and Work:</em></li>\n<li>Character 1: A stay-at-home mother who feels unappreciated and overwhelmed by the constant demands of housework and childcare.</li>\n<li>Character 2: Her partner who recognizes the value of her work and actively shares household responsibilities.</li>\n<li><em>Target 5.5 - Women’s Participation and Opportunities:</em></li>\n<li>Character 1: A qualified woman passed over for a promotion in favor of a less experienced male colleague.</li>\n<li>Character 2: A female CEO who mentors and empowers other women to break the glass ceiling.</li>\n<li><em>Target 5.6 - Universal Access and Rights:</em></li>\n<li>Character 1: A teenager in a rural area with limited access to sexual health education and contraceptives.</li>\n<li>Character 2: A healthcare provider who travels to remote communities to offer reproductive health services and information.</li>\n<li><em>Target 5.a - Economic Resources:</em></li>\n<li>Character 1: A woman denied a loan to start her own business because she doesn't have a male co-signer.</li>\n<li>Character 2: A successful businesswoman who invests in and supports female entrepreneurs.</li>\n<li><em>Target 5.b - Tech for Empowerment:</em></li>\n<li>Character 1: A girl in a remote village who has never used a computer or the internet.</li>\n<li>Character 2: A tech-savvy volunteer who teaches digital literacy skills to women and girls.</li>\n<li><em>Target 5.c - Policies for Gender Equality:</em></li>\n<li><em>Character 1: A lawmaker who is passionate about advocating for policies that promote gender equality.</em></li>\n<li><em>Character 2: A grassroots activist who organizes rallies and petitions to push for legislative change.</em></li>\n</ul></p>"} {sdgColor} />

	<CustomSection title={"Scriptwriting: Conversations for Change"} content={"<p>Have students begin to craft dialogue, by guiding them through writing a short script (1-2 pages) featuring a conversation between their two characters.<br>Focus on conflict and resolution by encouraging students to explore the challenges related to their target and potential solutions or actions that can lead to positive change.<br>Example dialogue prompts:\n<ul>\n<li><em>Target 5.1</em></li>\n<li>A conversation between a young woman applying for a job and an interviewer who makes sexist remarks and assumptions about her capabilities.</li>\n<li>A dialogue between two friends discussing the unequal treatment of girls and boys in their school or community.</li>\n<li>A debate between a student and a teacher about the importance of gender-neutral language and inclusive practices in the classroom.</li>\n<li><em>Target 5.2</em></li>\n<li>A conversation between a survivor of domestic violence and a supportive friend, exploring the complexities of seeking help and breaking the cycle of abuse.</li>\n<li>A conversation between a group of friends discussing a recent incident of sexual harassment or assault in their community, highlighting the fear and vulnerability experienced by women and girls.</li>\n<li>A dialogue between a police officer and a victim of domestic violence, exploring the challenges of reporting abuse and seeking justice.</li>\n<li><em>Target 5.3</em></li>\n<li>A dialogue between a girl who is being forced into marriage and her grandmother who tries to convince her to embrace tradition.</li>\n<li>A conversation between two friends discussing the dangers and consequences of female genital mutilation, with one advocating for change and the other defending cultural practices.</li>\n<li>A scene at a community meeting where a health worker educates villagers about the harmful effects of child marriage and offers alternative pathways for girls.</li>\n<li><em>Target 5.4</em></li>\n<li>A conversation between a husband and wife about the division of household chores and childcare responsibilities, highlighting the invisible labor often performed by women.</li>\n<li>A dialogue between a caregiver for an elderly parent and a friend, expressing the emotional and physical toll of unpaid care work.</li>\n<li>A debate between two policymakers about the need for social protection policies and public services to support those engaged in unpaid care work.</li>\n<li><em>Target 5.5</em></li>\n<li>A debate between two colleagues about a woman’s qualifications for a leadership position, highlighting unconscious bias and advocating for equal opportunities.</li>\n<li>A scene in a boardroom meeting where a woman's ideas are repeatedly dismissed or interrupted by her male colleagues.</li>\n<li>A conversation between two young girls discussing their dreams for the future and the obstacles they anticipate facing because of their gender.</li>\n<li><em>Target 5.6</em></li>\n<li>A conversation between two teenagers discussing the importance of safe sex and access to contraceptives.</li>\n<li>A dialogue between a woman seeking an abortion and a healthcare provider who is legally or morally opposed to the procedure.</li>\n<li>A debate between two community members about the inclusion of comprehensive sex education in schools.</li>\n<li><em>Target 5.a</em></li>\n<li>A dialogue between a woman farmer and a local official, discussing her challenges in accessing land ownership and financial resources.</li>\n<li>A dialogue between a woman and a bank loan officer who denies her application based on her marital status or lack of collateral.</li>\n<li>A conversation between a daughter and her father who refuses to include her in decisions about the family's land and property, upholding traditional inheritance practices.</li>\n<li><em>Target 5.b</em></li>\n<li>A conversation between a girl in a remote village who has never used a computer or the internet.</li>\n<li>A dialogue between a woman entrepreneur using technology to grow her business and a traditional business owner who is skeptical about its benefits.</li>\n<li>A scene in a classroom where students are learning about the digital divide and how it affects women's access to information and opportunities.</li>\n<li><em>Target 5.c</em></li>\n<li>A conversation between two activists strategizing about how to lobby for a new law promoting gender equality.</li>\n<li>A debate between a politician who supports gender quotas and one who believes they are unnecessary.</li>\n<li>A dialogue between a teacher and a student discussing the importance of gender-sensitive policies in schools and workplaces.</li>\n</ul></p>"} {sdgColor} />

	<CustomSection title={"Performance and Peer Feedback"} content={"<p>Have each group perform their script for the class. Students can fully act or just simply “table read” if they prefer.<br>After each script is read, encourage peers to provide feedback focusing on:\n<ul>\n<li><em>Clarity of Message</em></li>\n<li>Did the dialogue effectively convey the challenges and potential solutions related to the target?</li>\n<li>Were the potential solutions or actions expressed in a way that was understandable and actionable?</li>\n<li>Was there a clear sense of progress or resolution in the conversation, or did it leave the audience feeling uncertain or unresolved?</li>\n</ul><br>Example Questions:\n<ul>\n<li><em>“</em>Did the conversation make it clear what the characters were struggling with in relation to gender equality?”</li>\n<li>\"Were there any specific lines or moments in the dialogue that highlighted potential solutions or ways to address the issue?\"</li>\n<li><em>Character Development</em></li>\n<li>Did the characters feel like real people with distinct personalities, motivations, and backgrounds?</li>\n<li>Was their dialogue believable and consistent with their character traits?</li>\n<li>Did the conversation reveal their inner conflicts, hopes, and fears?</li>\n</ul><br>Example Questions:\n<ul>\n<li>\"Did you feel like you could relate to the characters and their experiences?\"</li>\n<li>\"Were there any specific lines or moments in the dialogue that revealed something important about the characters' personalities or motivations?\"</li>\n<li><em>Impact</em></li>\n<li>Did the scene evoke an emotional response in the audience?</li>\n<li>Did it spark empathy and understanding for the characters and their struggles?</li>\n<li>Did the conversation inspire you to think about the issue in a new way or consider taking action?</li>\n</ul><br>Example Questions:\n<ul>\n<li>\"How did this scene make you feel? What specific moments resonated with you?\"</li>\n<li>\"Did the dialogue make you think about the issue of gender equality in a different way?\"</li>\n<li>\"Do you feel inspired to do something about the challenges presented in the scene?\"</li>\n<li><em>Additional Feedback Prompts</em></li>\n<li>Was the dialogue natural and engaging?</li>\n<li>Did the conversation flow smoothly, or were there any awkward or confusing moments?</li>\n<li>Was the scene well-paced, with a clear beginning, middle, and end?</li>\n<li>Did the group use creative approaches to address the target and engage the audience?</li>\n<li>Were there any unique or unexpected moments in the dialogue or performance?</li>\n<li>What was the most powerful or memorable aspect of the scene?</li>\n<li>What would you like to see more of or explore further in relation to this target?</li>\n</ul></p>"} {sdgColor} />

	<CustomSection title={"Reflection and Summary"} content={"<p>Have students reflect on their learning experience through discussion or writing.<br>Ask guiding questions like:\n<ul>\n<li>How did writing dialogue between two characters with contrasting viewpoints deepen your understanding of the complexities surrounding gender equality?</li>\n<li>What did you learn about the different perspectives and experiences related to Global Goal 5 by writing from those viewpoints?</li>\n<li>How did you navigate the challenge of creating believable arguments for a perspective you might not personally agree with?</li>\n<li>What did you notice about the role of active listening and questioning in trying to understand your partner’s perspective during the warm-up and the script work?</li>\n<li>How can understanding contrasting viewpoints, as we explored in our dialogues, contribute to more productive conversations about gender equality in the real world?</li>\n<li>What broader themes related to gender equality emerged from different dialogues shared by the class?</li>\n<li>Did the process of writing and hearing these scenes spark any new insights about the interconnectedness of various targets within Global Goal 5?</li>\n<li>How did the dialogues explore the obstacles and opportunities for achieving a more gender-equal world?</li>\n<li>Did writing or hearing these dialogues resonate with any of your own observations or experiences related to gender equality in your life or community?</li>\n<li>What emotions did you connect with while creating or listening to these conversations about gender-related challenges and potential change?</li>\n<li>What are some ways you can use the power of conversation and storytelling to promote understanding and challenge gender inequality in your own interactions and community?</li>\n</ul></p>"} {sdgColor} />

	<CustomSection title={"Assessment"} content={"<ul>\n<li>Consistent and enthusiastic involvement in all phases of the lesson, including the “Finding Common Ground” warm-up, character creation, scriptwriting, and active participation in discussions (including peer feedback).</li>\n<li>Comprehension of Global Goal 5, targets and core concepts (e.g., discrimination, violence, leadership, economic resources). This will be evidenced through the thematic content and specific arguments/perspectives within the duologue scripts.</li>\n<li>Originality and effectiveness in crafting short duologue scripts that utilize dialogue to develop distinct characters, present contrasting viewpoints, and explore a specific aspect of gender inequality.</li>\n<li>How clearly and powerfully the dialogue communicated its intended message about Global Goal 5. Did the conversation successfully evoke empathy or provoke thought in the audience/readers?</li>\n<li>How well two distinct characters were created, with believable motivations and voices, effectively using dialogue to reveal the personalities and experiences related to gender equality.</li>\n<li>Ability to work effectively within pairs, brainstorming ideas, crafting dialogue, and providing constructive feedback (if applicable) during the scriptwriting and peer review process.</li>\n<li>Clarity of speech, emotional portrayal, and overall engagement when performing or reading the duologues aloud, effectively bringing the overall characters and conflict to life.</li>\n<li>Nuance and depth of understanding demonstrated in reflections, particularly concerning the rol eof dialogue in addressing gender inequality and fostering empathy.</li>\n</ul>"} {sdgColor} />

</div>
